{
  "//": "Present Simple — teoría y reglas",
  "id": "present-simple",
  "title": "Present Simple",
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "intro",
      "content": "El **Present Simple** se usa para hablar de rutinas, hechos generales y verdades universales."
    },
    {
      "type": "usage",
      "title": "📌 Usos principales",
      "items": [
        {
          "label": "Rutinas y hábitos",
          "example": "I *wake up* at 7 every day.",
          "note": "Acciones que se repiten"
        },
        {
          "label": "Hechos generales",
          "example": "Water *boils* at 100°C.",
          "note": "Verdades universales"
        },
        {
          "label": "Horarios",
          "example": "The bus *leaves* at 6 PM.",
          "note": "Horarios fijos"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "affirmative",
      "title": "✅ Affirmative",
      "rules": [
        {
          "subject": "I / You / We / They",
          "form": "verb (base form)",
          "examples": ["I play tennis.", "They live in Murcia."]
        },
        {
          "subject": "He / She / It",
          "form": "verb + -s / -es",
          "examples": ["He plays tennis.", "She watches TV.", "It rains a lot."],
          "notes": [
            "-s: play → plays",
            "-es: watch → watches ( -sh, -ch, -ss, -x, -o )",
            "-ies: study → studies ( consonante + y → -ies )"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "negative",
      "title": "❌ Negative",
      "rules": [
        {
          "subject": "I / You / We / They",
          "form": "subject + don't + verb",
          "examples": ["I don't like coffee.", "They don't live here."]
        },
        {
          "subject": "He / She / It",
          "form": "subject + doesn't + verb (sin -s)",
          "examples": ["He doesn't play football.", "She doesn't eat meat."],
          "note": "¡Importante! Tras doesn't el verbo vuelve a la forma base (sin -s)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "questions",
      "title": "❓ Questions",
      "rules": [
        {
          "form": "Do / Does + subject + verb?",
          "examples": [
            "Do you like pizza? → Yes, I do. / No, I don't.",
            "Does he speak English? → Yes, he does. / No, he doesn't."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "signal-words",
      "title": "🔑 Signal words (palabras clave)",
      "items": [
        "always", "usually", "often", "sometimes", "rarely", "never",
        "every day / week / month",
        "once a week", "twice a month",
        "in the morning / afternoon / evening",
        "on Mondays / at weekends"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "ps-1",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "She ___ (play) tennis every Sunday.",
      "answer": "plays"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-2",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "They ___ (not / like) coffee.",
      "answer": "don't like"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-3",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "___ he ___ (speak) French?",
      "answer": "Does speak",
      "alts": ["Does ... speak"]
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-4",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "My father ___ (work) in an office.",
      "answer": "works"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-5",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "We ___ (not / go) to school on Sundays.",
      "answer": "don't go"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-6",
      "type": "reorder",
      "stem": "Ordena: always / I / coffee / drink / in the morning",
      "answer": "I always drink coffee in the morning."
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-7",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "She ___ (study) English at school.",
      "answer": "studies"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-8",
      "type": "choice",
      "stem": "He ___ (go) to the gym on Fridays.",
      "answer": "goes",
      "options": ["go", "goes", "going", "gone"]
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-9",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "___ you ___ (want) a drink?",
      "answer": "Do want"
    },
    {
      "id": "ps-10",
      "type": "gap",
      "stem": "The train ___ (leave) at 9:00 AM.",
      "answer": "leaves"
    }
  ],
  "tips": [
    "El verbo en 3ª persona singular lleva -s: he plays, she works, it rains.",
    "Con 'doesn't' el verbo NUNCA lleva -s: he doesn't play (no 'he doesn't plays').",
    "Los adverbios de frecuencia van ANTES del verbo: I always eat breakfast.",
    "Pero van DESPUÉS del verbo 'to be': I am never late."
  ]
}
